Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: Existing benchmarks like RobuT, FREB-TQA, and ADVETA have made important strides in evaluating TableQA robustness by introducing adversarial perturbations—particularly on questions, table structure, or content. However, they often treat robustness as a monolithic property or focus on isolated aspects (e.g., numerical reasoning or structural invariance). A key gap remains: there is no unified diagnostic framework that not only applies diverse, human-annotated perturbations across *all* components (headers, cells, questions) but also disentangles model failure modes into interpretable dimensions such as *semantic coherence*, *structural awareness*, *contextual grounding*, and *reasoning fidelity*. Furthermore, most benchmarks rely on perturbing existing datasets without modeling how real-world users naturally introduce ambiguity or noise during interaction. My idea builds upon these works by proposing TAB-ROBUST—a benchmark grounded in cognitive and linguistic principles of human error patterns, where perturbations are systematically categorized and annotated for *intent* and *impact type*. This enables fine-grained diagnostics beyond accuracy drops, allowing researchers to pinpoint *why* models fail. Unlike prior work, TAB-ROBUST integrates a multi-axis perturbation taxonomy co-designed with domain experts and crowd workers, ensuring realism and coverage. It also introduces "perturbation chains"—sequential modifications that simulate cumulative user-induced noise—pushing models beyond single-point robustness. Finally, it includes a diagnostic probe suite to attribute failures to specific architectural weaknesses (e.g., over-reliance on header semantics vs. cell values). This transforms robustness evaluation from a stress test into a mechanistic analysis tool.

